title: Ask HN: Do you read books about frameworks?
text:
Hello everyone!

I’m a business informatics student and working part time for a company as a web developer.

I started to read books about Programming as I started my university. But I noticed that I need books for remembering things that I read. I’m now buying a book every month and can freely write notes and stick the little colorful things on them to highlight a page.

I made a list of books but I noticed that there are few books about frameworks in my list. Like Spring In Action or Pro Django.

My question is, does it make sense buying books about frameworks or getting more high level books like The Clean Code, Design Patterns or maybe both?

Ask HN: Best practices for using email to log in to important online services
text:
I might be overthinking this but it seems to me that using your email account both as a tool to communicate and as your personal identifier to log in to critical online services like bank accounts or password managers is problematic.

Is using 2FA in both my email account (although, if I'm not mistaken, 2FA doesn't work for POP3/IMAP accounts) and in, let's say, my bank account a reasonably secure option that address the apparent contradiction of using a public identifier (i.e. email account) for something that should be kept private (part of the information required to access your money, tax information, etc.)?

Do you have email addresses/aliases that you use exclusively as usernames for critical/important online services and not for communicating? Are there "best practices" when it comes to separating the use of email as a communication tool and as personal identifier/username? How do you manage this?

Or, as I said at the beggining, am I overthinking this?

Ask HN: A few questions regarding The Lean Startup
text:
Question #1: do you know of any Entrepreneurs who has build, or is building a company using The Lean Startup methodology who has blogged (or is blogging) about the adventure in real time as events happen?

Question #2: do you know if anyone has developed a how-to manual out of The Lean Startup book? Or a course? Or something more concrete and practical? While I understand that it's not a paint-by-number type of endeavor, I was wondering is there was something more practical with less theory, and less post-mortem.

TIA

title: Ask HN: Looking for a diagram/graph renderer similar to graphviz/dot
text:
I want to find a CLI text->png diagram renderer. It runs on Linux.

I have seen this software before, but I couldn't find it now. Maybe some of you know what the software is called?

## Example 1: https://envs.sh/Qfj.png

This diagram is created with something like ``` ellipse line ellipse ```

there is no concept of "edge/node" in this software.

## Example 2: https://envs.sh/Qfc.png

This diagram is created with something like ``` set direction to right ellipse set direction to down ellipse ```

This behavior is different from graphviz.

Ask HN: Industries in need of better consumer protection
text:
Hi all,

I've been debating with friends and wanted to get HN's perspective about the industries for which consumer rights need to be better protected.

While it's tempting to say "all of them" I'd like to solitic your specific examples.

Is it our data? Is it our behavioural patterns and privacy? Is it the insurance industry - which exact part?

What about new technologies or companies (besides the obvious giants) that hold great power / monopoly power?

I know it's an open-ended question but I'd really value your thoughts.

TY
